		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div><p>I agree that Warriors need a downward scaling tool, but it's not entirely acurate to compare a self-heal directly to a Warrior's -1 DI alone.</p><p>First, There are many other factor's involved other then the -1 DI, that is not the only difference between a Warrior and a knight.</p><p>Second, there is greater value to mitigation and avoidance. Not getting hit is far better then healing up after you take the damage. While Self healing can make a knight more efficent, it does not always make them safer or better as tanks.</p><p>Third, Redundancy. There are other people in any group, not just a Healer and a Tank. Many of these classes have heals. When a Warrior tanks there could be a Ranger, Beast Lord, Shaman, Druid, Paladin etc as well as the main healer. Paladin heals are good, but they can also be redundant, replace the Paladin in the group and put in a Warrior for example, there is no reason why the Ranger can't perform patch heals on the Warrior where the knight was doing it himself. I point this out because Healing is a tertiary role outside of Tanking, <strong>if it can be performed by another group member then factoring our heals into the tanking equation is not accurate</strong>.</p><p>Fourth, Low impact groups. In such low impact groups such as what you refer to when scaling downwards, our self heals are entirely redundant, as the incoming damage is not remotely comparible to the mana supply of the main and secondary healers.<strong> In short any Paladin heals cast in trivial content is just Wasting Mana.</strong></p><p>Fifth, one could well point out that Warriors bring higher DPS to the group which is far more valuable to redundant paladin healsin low impact groups.</p>	
		</td></tr>
